          "body": "Read as one composition, Matthew 15 makes a single argument about who inherits the kingdom. Lip-religion that voids God's commandment for the sake of tradition (15:1-9) is exposed as far-from-God hypocrisy. The defilement Israel's leaders feared from unwashed hands is, in reality, oozing from their own hearts (15:10-20). Meanwhile, a Canaanite mother's heart-faith — argumentative, persistent, theologically agile — receives instantly what the leaders are refused (15:21-28); and Gentile-region crowds glorify the God of Israel and eat the Messiah's bread (15:29-39). The chapter is the narrative version of what Paul will later argue in Romans 9-11 and Ephesians 2-3: physical Israel's leaders are not the planting of the Father if their hearts are far; the nations who come in faith are the planting He acknowledges. Matthew 15 is not anti-Jewish; it is anti-hypocrisy. The line runs not between Jew and Gentile but between the heart that honors and the lips that merely speak."
